Title: The Special Credit Unit (SCU) – Overview and Purpose

Content:

What is the SCU?
The Special Credit Unit is a sub-function within Wholesale Credit Risk Management (WCRM) specializing in the negotiation of credit-related solutions for wholesale customers showing signs of financial distress.

Main Objective:
To protect the bank’s credit portfolio by managing and restructuring problematic exposures through proactive engagement and strategic resolution.

Key Roles:

Support Business and Credit teams when deterioration in credit quality occurs.

Develop tailored credit strategies for distressed customers.

Coordinate recovery or turnaround actions with all stakeholders.




---

SLIDE 2 – SCU Engagement Process

Title: How and When SCU Gets Involved

Content:

Triggered by: Early warning indicators from the Watch / Worry / Monitor (WWM) process or other deterioration signals (e.g., covenant breaches, financial stress, IFRS-9 triggers).

Types of Engagement:

1. Turnaround Cases – Customers in temporary distress, where rehabilitation or refinancing can return them to standard management.


2. Debt Recovery Cases – Customers in insolvency or legal recovery processes, where resolution or debt sale is required.



During Engagement:

SCU leads the credit strategy.

Business Relationship Managers retain account management but follow SCU guidance.

Clear data-exchange and responsibility protocols are established between SCU and Business teams.




---

SLIDE 3 – Value & Collaboration

Title: Why SCU Matters

Content:

Prevents Credit Losses: Enables early, structured interventions before defaults escalate.

Ensures Governance: Maintains compliance with HSBC’s Credit Policy and IFRS-9 framework.

Promotes Collaboration: Works alongside the Credit Approval Unit (CAU) and WCRM to ensure consistent, controlled treatment of high-risk exposures.

Outcome: Restores customer viability, manages exits efficiently, and protects the bank’s balance sheet.

